' class='math-display' src='paper_simulation_r192x.svg' /><a id='x1-8002r2'></a></div>   
</td><td class='equation-label'>(2)</td></tr></table>
<!-- l. 217 --><p class='nopar'>where <span class='cmr-12'>Φ </span>is the standard normal CDF. This fraction decreases rapidly: <span class='cmr-12'>34% </span>at <span class='cmmi-12'>d </span><span class='cmr-12'>= 10</span>,
but only <span class='cmr-12'>0</span><span class='cmmi-12'>.</span><span class='cmr-12'>03% </span>at <span class='cmmi-12'>d </span><span class='cmr-12'>= 150</span>. The transitional (inter-basin) region therefore dominates
genotype space in high dimensions—it is the <span class='ec-lmri-12'>basins</span>, not the corridors, that have low
measure.
</p><!-- l. 223 --><p class='indent'>   <strong>Remark on the max-form basin.</strong> The basin bonus <span class='cmr-12'>max(</span><span class='cmmi-12'>e</span><sup><span class='cmsy-8'>−</span><span class='cmr-8'>2</span><span class='cmmi-8'>ḡ</span><sup><span class='cmr-6'>2</span></sup></sup><span class='cmmi-12'>,e</span><sup><span class='cmsy-8'>−</span><span class='cmr-8'>2(1</span><span class='cmsy-8'>−</span><span class='cmmi-8'>ḡ</span><span class='cmr-8'>)</span><sup><span class='cmr-6'>2</span></sup></sup><span class='cmr-12'>) </span>is piecewise smooth
with a kink at <span class='cmmi-12'>ḡ </span><span class='cmr-12'>= 1</span><span class='cmmi-12'>∕</span><span class='cmr-12'>2</span>. This “Regime II” geometry (kinked boundary saddle) is covered by
Theorem 2.10 and Corollary 2.15 of <a href='#XNashida2026b'>Nashida</a> (<a href='#XNashida2026b'>2026b</a>), using the explicit <span class='cmmi-12'>K </span><span class='cmr-12'>= 0 </span>asymptotics of
<a href='#XNashida2026a'>Nashida</a> (<a href='#XNashida2026a'>2026a</a>); the K-independence result therefore applies without modification (see
Section <a href='#universality-epistasis-independence-of-regime-boundaries'>4.5<!-- tex4ht:ref: sec:K_sensitivity  --></a>).
</p><!-- l. 230 --><p class='noindent'>
</p>   
<h4 class='subsectionHead' id='evolutionary-dynamics'><span class='titlemark'>3.2   </span> <a id='x1-90003.2'></a>Evolutionary dynamics</h4>
                                                                                          
                                                                                          
<!-- l. 232 --><p class='noindent'>We simulate a single lineage in the weak-mutation limit (<span class='cmmi-12'>Nμ </span><span class='cmsy-10x-x-120'>≪ </span><span class='cmr-12'>1</span>): at each step, one random locus
is flipped, and the mutant is accepted with Metropolis probability <span class='cmr-12'>min(1</span><span class='cmmi-12'>, </span><span class='cmr-12'>exp(</span><span class='cmmi-12'>s</span><sub>coeff</sub> <span class='cmsy-10x-x-120'>⋅ </span><span class='cmr-12'>Δ</span><span class='cmmi-12'>w</span><span class='cmr-12'>)) </span>where
<span class='cmmi-12'>s</span><sub>coeff</sub> <span class='cmr-12'>= 5</span><span class='cmmi-12'>.</span><span class='cmr-12'>0 </span>is a dimensionless selection strength independent of <span class='cmmi-12'>d</span>. Each simulation is initialized
near basin 1 by setting <span class='cmsy-10x-x-120'>∼ </span><span class='cmr-12'>10% </span>of randomly chosen loci to 1 (yielding <span class='cmmi-12'>ḡ </span><span class='cmsy-10x-x-120'>≈ </span><span class='cmr-12'>0</span><span class='cmmi-12'>.</span><span class='cmr-12'>1</span>). The fitness
landscape is symmetric under basin exchange, so initialization does not bias regime
classification.
</p><!-- l. 241 --><p class='indent'>   <strong>Transition definitions.</strong> A <span class='ec-lmri-12'>complete transition </span>is a basin <span class='cmmi-12'>X </span><span class='cmsy-10x-x-120'>→ </span>transitional <span class='cmsy-10x-x-120'>→ </span>basin <span class='cmmi-12'>Y</span>
sequence with <span class='cmmi-12'>X≠Y </span>. Stasis duration <span class='cmmi-12'>τ</span><sub>stasis</sub> is the number of consecutive steps in one basin
between successive complete transitions; transit duration <span class='cmmi-12'>τ</span><sub>transit</sub> is the number of steps in the
transitional zone during a complete transition. Points with <span class='cmmi-12'>n</span><sub>tr</sub> <span class='cmr-12'>= 0 </span>are classified as frozen. Phase
boundaries <span class='cmmi-12'>β</span><sub>high</sub><sup><span class='cmsy-8'>∗</span></sup><span class='cmr-12'>(</span><span class='cmmi-12'>d</span><span class='cmr-12'>) </span>(lowest <span class='cmmi-12'>β </span>with zero transitions in all replicates) and <span class='cmmi-12'>β</span><sub>low</sub><sup><span class='cmsy-8'>∗</span></sup><span class='cmr-12'>(</span><span class='cmmi-12'>d</span><span class='cmr-12'>) </span>(highest <span class='cmmi-12'>β </span>at
which the system remains non-frozen, i.e., total <span class='cmmi-12'>n</span><sub>tr</sub> <span class='cmmi-12'>&gt; </span><span class='cmr-12'>0</span>) are determined from Exp. 1 and
Exp. 2 data. Table <a href='#-regime-boundaries-and-punctuated-band-width-as-a-function-of-dimensiond-primary-experiment-exp-replicates-steps-for-d-exp-replicates-steps-for-d-punct-lowest-with-ratio-punctuatedband-lower-boundary-high-lowest-with-zero-transitions-in-allreplicates-frozen-boundary'>1<!-- tex4ht:ref: tab:regimes  --></a> additionally reports <span class='cmmi-12'>β</span><sub>punct</sub>, the lowest <span class='cmmi-12'>β </span>at which the stasis/transit
ratio exceeds the punctuated threshold (ratio <span class='cmmi-12'>&gt; </span><span class='cmr-12'>10</span>); this is a distinct quantity from
<span class='cmmi-12'>β</span><sub>low</sub><sup><span class='cmsy-8'>∗</span></sup>.
</p><!-- l. 256 --><p class='indent'>   <strong>Observational implications.</strong> The detection probability of transitional forms follows a Poisson
process: <span class='cmmi-12'>p</span><sub>detect</sub> <span class='cmsy-10x-x-120'>≈ </span><span class='cmmi-12'>r </span><span class='cmsy-10x-x-120'>⋅ </span><span class='cmmi-12'>s</span><sub>sample</sub> <span class='cmsy-10x-x-120'>⋅ </span><span class='cmr-12'>ln </span><span class='cmmi-12'>N</span><sub><span class='cmmi-8'>e</span></sub><span class='cmmi-12'>∕</span><span class='cmr-12'>(2</span><span class='cmmi-12'>s</span><sup><span class='cmr-8'>2</span></sup><span class='cmr-12'>)</span>, where <span class='cmmi-12'>r </span>is the fossilization rate, <span class='cmmi-12'>s</span><sub>sample</sub>
is the stratigraphic sampling density, <span class='cmmi-12'>N</span><sub><span class='cmmi-8'>e</span></sub> is the effective population size, and <span class='cmmi-12'>s </span>is the
per-allele selection coefficient (distinct from the simulation parameter <span class='cmmi-12'>s</span><sub>coeff</sub>). Under
typical paleontological parameters (<a href='#XFoote1996'>Foote and Raup</a>, <a href='#XFoote1996'>1996</a>) (<span class='cmmi-12'>r </span><span class='cmsy-10x-x-120'>∼ </span><span class='cmr-12'>10</span><sup><span class='cmsy-8'>−</span><span class='cmr-8'>7</span></sup>, <span class='cmmi-12'>s</span><sub>sample</sub> <span class='cmsy-10x-x-120'>∼ </span><span class='cmr-12'>10</span><sup><span class='cmsy-8'>−</span><span class='cmr-8'>3</span></sup>,
<span class='cmmi-12'>N</span><sub><span class='cmmi-8'>e</span></sub> <span class='cmsy-10x-x-120'>∼ </span><span class='cmr-12'>10</span><sup><span class='cmr-8'>5</span></sup>, <span class='cmmi-12'>s </span><span class='cmsy-10x-x-120'>∼ </span><span class='cmr-12'>10</span><sup><span class='cmsy-8'>−</span><span class='cmr-8'>2</span></sup>), <span class='cmmi-12'>p</span><sub>detect</sub> <span class='cmsy-10x-x-120'>≈ </span><span class='cmr-12'>6 </span><span class='cmsy-10x-x-120'>× </span><span class='cmr-12'>10</span><sup><span class='cmsy-8'>−</span><span class='cmr-8'>6</span></sup>—confirming that transitional forms are effectively
undetectable. However, low detection probability does <span class='ec-lmri-12'>not </span>by itself imply punctuated
equilibrium: the dynamical prerequisite—the existence of a punctuated regime—fails at high
<span class='cmmi-12'>d</span>.
</p><!-- l. 269 --><p class='noindent'>
</p>   
<h4 class='subsectionHead' id='parameter-space-exploration'><span class='titlemark'>3.3   </span> <a id='x1-100003.3'></a>Parameter space exploration</h4>
<!-- l. 271 --><p class='noindent'>The primary experiment (Exp. 1) systematically explored the <span class='cmr-12'>(</span><span class='cmmi-12'>d,β</span><span class='cmr-12'>) </span>parameter space:
</p>      
<ul class='itemize1'>
<li class='itemize'>Dimensions: <span class='cmmi-12'>d </span><span class='cmsy-10x-x-120'>∈{</span><span class='cmr-12'>10</span><span class='cmmi-12'>, </span><span class='cmr-12'>20</span><span class='cmmi-12'>, </span><span class='cmr-12'>40</span><span class='cmmi-12'>, </span><span class='cmr-12'>60</span><span class='cmmi-12'>, </span><span class='cmr-12'>80</span><span class='cmmi-12'>, </span><span class='cmr-12'>100</span><span class='cmmi-12'>, </span><span class='cmr-12'>120</span><span class='cmmi-12'>, </span><span class='cmr-12'>150</span><span class='cmmi-12'>, </span><span class='cmr-12'>200</span><span class='cmmi-12'>, </span><span class='cmr-12'>300</span><span class='cmsy-10x-x-120'>}</span>
</li>
<li class='itemize'>Basin depths: 29 <span class='cmmi-12'>β</span>-values from 0.5 to 128
</li>
<li class='itemize'>Total: 290 grid points, each with 30 replicates of <span class='cmr-12'>5 </span><span class='cmsy-10x-x-120'>× </span><span class='cmr-12'>10</span><sup><span class='cmr-8'>6</span></sup> mutation steps
                                                                                          
                                                                                          
      
</li>      
<li class='itemize'>Bootstrap 95% confidence intervals computed for all summary statistics</li></ul>
<!-- l. 279 --><p class='noindent'>
</p>   
<h4 class='subsectionHead' id='additional-experiments'><span class='titlemark'>3.4   </span> <a id='x1-110003.4'></a>Additional experiments</h4>
<!-- l. 281 --><p class='noindent'>The following experiments (Exp. 2–4) support the core results reported in the main
text. Experiments 5–9 are summarized in Supplementary Table S1 and Supplementary
Figures S1–S6.
</p><!-- l. 285 --><p class='indent'>   <strong>(2) Dimension precision scan.</strong> <span class='cmmi-12'>d </span><span class='cmsy-10x-x-120'>∈{</span><span class='cmr-12'>12</span><span class='cmmi-12'>, </span><span class='cmr-12'>14</span><span class='cmmi-12'>, </span><span class='cmr-12'>16</span><span class='cmmi-12'>, </span><span class='cmr-12'>18</span><span class='cmsy-10x-x-120'>} </span>at 13 <span class='cmmi-12'>β</span>-values with 30 replicates of
<span class='cmr-12'>5 </span><span class='cmsy-10x-x-120'>× </span><span class='cmr-12'>10</span><sup><span class='cmr-8'>6</span></sup> steps (1,560 runs), locating the precise dimension at which the punctuated band
vanishes.
</p><!-- l. 289 --><p class='indent'>   <strong>(3) Extended large-d runs.</strong> <span class='cmmi-12'>d </span><span class='cmsy-10x-x-120'>∈{</span><span class='cmr-12'>80</span><span class='cmmi-12'>, </span><span class='cmr-12'>150</span><span class='cmmi-12'>, </span><span class='cmr-12'>300</span><span class='cmsy-10x-x-120'>} </span>at 14 <span class='cmmi-12'>β</span>-values, with 50 replicates of <span class='cmr-12'>2 </span><span class='cmsy-10x-x-120'>× </span><span class='cmr-12'>10</span><sup><span class='cmr-8'>7</span></sup>
steps (2,100 runs; <span class='cmr-12'>10</span><sup><span class='cmr-8'>9</span></sup> steps per <span class='cmr-12'>(</span><span class='cmmi-12'>d,β</span><span class='cmr-12'>) </span>point), confirming that <span class='cmmi-12'>n</span><sub>tr</sub> <span class='cmr-12'>= 0 </span>at high <span class='cmmi-12'>d </span>reflects true
freezing rather than insufficient observation time.
</p><!-- l. 294 --><p class='indent'>   <strong>(4) Epistasis sensitivity (K).</strong> <span class='cmmi-12'>K </span><span class='cmsy-10x-x-120'>∈{</span><span class='cmr-12'>0</span><span class='cmmi-12'>, </span><span class='cmr-12'>2</span><span class='cmmi-12'>, </span><span class='cmr-12'>4</span><span class='cmmi-12'>, </span><span class='cmr-12'>8</span><span class='cmmi-12'>, </span><span class='cmr-12'>16</span><span class='cmsy-10x-x-120'>} </span>at <span class='cmmi-12'>d </span><span class='cmsy-10x-x-120'>∈{</span><span class='cmr-12'>10</span><span class='cmmi-12'>, </span><span class='cmr-12'>20</span><span class='cmmi-12'>, </span><span class='cmr-12'>40</span><span class='cmmi-12'>, </span><span class='cmr-12'>80</span><span class='cmmi-12'>, </span><span class='cmr-12'>150</span><span class='cmsy-10x-x-120'>} </span>with 8 <span class='cmmi-12'>β</span>-values
and 20 replicates per point (3,840 runs), testing whether regime boundaries depend on microscopic
epistatic structure.
</p><!-- l. 300 --><p class='noindent'>
</p>   
<h3 class='sectionHead' id='results'><span class='titlemark'>4   </span> <a id='x1-120004'></a>Results</h3>
<!-- l. 303 --><p class='noindent'>
</p>   
<h4 class='subsectionHead' id='three-dynamical-regimes'><span class='titlemark'>4.1   </span> <a id='x1-130004.1'></a>Three dynamical regimes</h4>
<!-- l. 305 --><p class='noindent'>Across all dimensions examined, increasing basin depth <span class='cmmi-12'>β </span>produces three sharply delineated
regimes (Fig. <a href='#-phase-diagram-of-evolutionary-dynamics-on-highdimensional-twobasin-fitness-landscapes-background-shading-indicates-the-dynamical-regime-determined-by-nearestneighbor-interpolation-of-simulation-data-cyan-diffusive-ratio-gold-marginal-ratio-rose-punctuated-ratio-grey-frozen-zero-transitions-in-all-replicates-blue-circles-with-line-lower-phase-boundary-low-highest-with-nonfrozen-dynamics-rose-squares-with-line-upper-phase-boundary-high-lowest-with-zero-transitions-in-all-replicates-the-punctuated-region-rose-is-visible-only-at-d-and-vanishes-at-higher-dimensions-data-from-exp-k-replicates-steps-per-replicate'>1<!-- tex4ht:ref: fig:phase_diagram  --></a>; characterization curves in Fig. <a href='#-regime-characterization-across-dimensions-astasistransit-ratio-vs-for-each-d-rose-dashed-line-ratio-punctuated-threshold-bnumber-of-complete-transitions-vs-cmean-stasis-duration-vs-each-curve-represents-one-dimension-d-see-legend-below-panels-curves-for-d-d-and-d-are-drawn-thicker-for-emphasis-all-other-curves-are-shown-as-thin-background-lines'>2<!-- tex4ht:ref: fig:regime_chars  --></a>):
</p><!-- l. 309 --><p class='indent'>   <strong>Diffusive regime</strong> (low <span class='cmmi-12'>β</span>): Populations traverse freely between basins. The stasis/transit ratio
is <span class='cmmi-12'>&lt; </span><span class='cmr-12'>5</span>, with thousands of complete transitions per simulation.
</p><!-- l. 312 --><p class='indent'>   <strong>Punctuated regime</strong> (intermediate <span class='cmmi-12'>β</span>): Populations exhibit prolonged stasis within basins,
interrupted by rare rapid transitions. The stasis/transit ratio exceeds <span class='cmr-12'>10</span>.
</p><!-- l. 316 --><p class='indent'>   <strong>Frozen regime</strong> (high <span class='cmmi-12'>β</span>): Populations are permanently trapped within a single basin; no
complete transitions occur.
</p><!-- l. 319 --><p class='indent'>   These three regimes are structurally parallel to the three-phase taxonomies reviewed in
Section <a href='#background'>2<!-- tex4ht:ref: sec:background  --></a> (Tarazona 1992; Kramers theory; Hwang et al. 2017). Our contribution is demonstrating
a concrete realization on high-dimensional discrete fitness landscapes where the intermediate regime
has a <span class='ec-lmri-12'>dimension-dependent width</span>.
                                                                                          
                                                                                          
</p>   
<figure class='figure' id='-phase-diagram-of-evolutionary-dynamics-on-highdimensional-twobasin-fitness-landscapes-background-shading-indicates-the-dynamical-regime-determined-by-nearestneighbor-interpolation-of-simulation-data-cyan-diffusive-ratio-gold-marginal-ratio-rose-punctuated-ratio-grey-frozen-zero-transitions-in-all-replicates-blue-circles-with-line-lower-phase-boundary-low-highest-with-nonfrozen-dynamics-rose-squares-with-line-upper-phase-boundary-high-lowest-with-zero-transitions-in-all-replicates-the-punctuated-region-rose-is-visible-only-at-d-and-vanishes-at-higher-dimensions-data-from-exp-k-replicates-steps-per-replicate'> 

                                                                                          
                                                                                          
